{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564027"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:08:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:08:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16928"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16928"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.52,0.15,0.31,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9618"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67799"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9618"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16928"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53264"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4112"},{"type":"tags","id":"4141"},{"type":"tags","id":"4179"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22702"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41804"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43669"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67799"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of vaginal heaviness and dragging sensation. She describes a bulge at the vaginal entrance that is worse when standing or straining and improves when lying down. She has occasional urinary urgency but no incontinence. She has had three vaginal deliveries and underwent menopause at age 52. Her medical history includes hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include amlodipine and paracetamol. Her BMI is 32 kg/m2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Pelvic examination reveals a anterior vaginal wall descent that protrudes 2 cm beyond the hymenal ring on Valsalva manoeuvre. The cervix remains well supported. There is no posterior vaginal wall descent.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enterocele","Cystocele","Uterine prolapse","Vaginal vault prolapse","Rectocele"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with typical symptoms of pelvic organ prolapse, with examination findings consistent with anterior compartment prolapse. \u003Cstrong\u003ECystocele\u003C/strong\u003E (anterior vaginal wall prolapse) occurs when the bladder descends into the anterior vaginal wall due to weakness of the pubocervical fascia. It is the most common type of pelvic organ prolapse, particularly in postmenopausal women with a history of vaginal deliveries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERectocele\u003C/strong\u003E involves posterior vaginal wall descent with herniation of the rectum. This would be visible as bulging of the posterior vaginal wall on examination, which is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUterine prolapse\u003C/strong\u003E involves descent of the cervix and uterus. While this can co-exist with other types of prolapse, the stem specifically notes that the cervix remains well supported.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaginal vault prolapse\u003C/strong\u003E can only occur in women who have had a hysterectomy, which is not mentioned in this patient\u0027s history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnterocele\u003C/strong\u003E is a herniation of peritoneal contents into the rectovaginal space, typically presenting as posterior vaginal wall descent between the cervix and rectum. This is not consistent with the anterior wall findings described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for pelvic organ prolapse include vaginal delivery, obesity, chronic straining (e.g., constipation, chronic cough), and menopause. The loss of oestrogen after menopause leads to decreased collagen content and elasticity of the pelvic floor tissues, contributing to prolapse development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pelvic organ prolapse commonly presents with a vaginal dragging sensation and/or a visible or palpable bulge at the vaginal introitus.","Cystocele (anterior vaginal wall prolapse) is the most common type of pelvic organ prolapse.","Risk factors for pelvic organ prolapse include vaginal delivery, obesity, chronic cough, and menopause."],"references":["Makajeva J, Watters C, Safioleas P. Cystocele. [Updated 2022 Oct 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK564303/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53264"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16928"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53264"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T10:02:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T10:03:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9618"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67799"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4112"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Pelvic organ prolapse","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-02T14:23:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-10T15:36:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4141"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cystocele","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-02T14:23:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-02T14:23:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type"